body:
- What OS, Python version?
- How did you install IPython?
- what is `PYTHONPATH`?
- what do you get from `python -m site`?
- ...and `head -n 1 $(which ipython)`?

The OS is Ubuntu 12.04, and Python version is python 2.7.

I installed the IPython via pip with the following command: sudo pip install ipython[notebook,zmq] --upgrade. It is upgraded from ipython 1.2, which is also installed via pip.

The original PYTHONPATH is empty when this problem appears. Now, the PYTHONPATH is the same with sys.path when ipython or python starts. The problem remains in both of these situations.

"python -m site" outputs nothing. 
"head -n 1 $(which ipython)" outputs "#!/usr/bin/python", and "/usr/bin/python" links to /usr/bin/python2.7.

Before this problem appears, I could use ipython notebook, and everything works well. I did not use ipython notebook for some time (maybe a couple of weeks), and when I use it today, the problem appears.

Another thing I forgot to mention is that there was also an very old version of ipython installed in /usr/lib/ and /usr/bin, which I think is installed through Ubuntu apt-get long time ago. But now, I already remove it through Ubuntu apt-get remove. Will this cause my problem? Thanks.

The odds are that you have multiple IPythons installed, and the subprocess is loading a different one from the parent. I'm not sure why that is, but the issue should not appear if you clear out older versions of IPython (e.g. uninstall with apt, then uninstall with pip until it doesn't find ipython anymore, then reinstall with pip).

Hi @minrk , I delete everything related to ipython, and reinstall them again via pip, but the same problem still remains. However, after I added the ipython installation path (/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/IPython in my case) to the environment variable PYTHONPATH, the problem goes away and I can successfully create and open notebook in the web browser. So, my guess is should the line where imports kernel.zmq.kernelapp module in ipython implementation be replaced by "import IPython.kernel.zmq.kernelapp"? Or, should the installation process add the installation path of IPython to the python library path so that the module kernel.zmq.kernelapp could be found by ipython? Thanks.

That's disturbing. I don't think `kernel.zmq.kernelapp` appears anywhere in the IPython codebase without being prefixed with `IPython`, so there's something unique about your system that is causing it to behave this way.

Do you get any more information if you start the notebook with `--debug`?

Do you think there is anything unusual with my laptop from this log information?

What you said confuses me too when I first saw the problem.

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<string>", line 1, in <module>
ImportError: No module named kernel.zmq.kernelapp
```

From this log information, the place where raise the error seems to be in a file called `<string>`. However, this file looks more likely to be a c++ file, not the python file. While, all the files in the IPython folder seems to be python files.

Hm, when you started the notebook with `--debug`, the problem didn't happen. Can you reproduce the problem with `--debug`?

> seems to be in a file called `<string>`.

That's a special name for when code comes from a string in memory, instead of an actual file.

@minrk Ah, I see. I think I know reason for the problem. Is it because there is a folder with name IPython in the directory where I create ipython notebook? After I delete that folder, the problem goes away.
aha, yes. That's how Python works - it looks in the local directory before anywhere else.

@minrk  I think the original problem may due to the multiple version of ipython in my laptop. But after I remove the older version, the problem is caused by the IPython folder in the local directory. My bad :). Thanks a lot for the help.
